<doc id="343663" wikidata="Q1131116" url="?curid=343663" title="Set-theoretic limit">
<text>In mathematics, the limit of a sequence of sets formula_1 (subsets of a common set formula_2) is a set whose elements are determined by the sequence in either of two equivalent ways: (1) by upper and lower bounds on the sequence that converge monotonically to the same set (analogous to convergence of real-valued sequences) and (2) by convergence of a sequence of indicator functions which are themselves real-valued. As is the case with sequences of other objects, convergence is not necessary or even usual.

More generally, again analogous to real-valued sequences, the less restrictive limit infimum and limit supremum of a set sequence always exist and can be used to determine convergence: the limit exists if the limit infimum and limit supremum are identical. (See below). Such set limits are essential in measure theory and probability.

It is a common misconception that the limits infimum and supremum described here involve sets of accumulation points, that is, sets of formula_3 where each formula_4 is in some formula_5 This is only true if convergence is determined by the discrete metric (that is, formula_6 if there is formula_7 such that formula_8 for all formula_9). This article is restricted to that situation as it is the only one relevant for measure theory and probability. See the examples below. (On the other hand, there are more general topological notions of set convergence that do involve accumulation points under different metrics or topologies.)

==Definitions==

===The two definitions===
Suppose that formula_10 is a sequence of sets. The two equivalent definitions are as follows.

* Using union and intersection: define formula_11 and formula_12 If these two sets are equal, then the set-theoretic limit of the sequence formula_13 exists and is equal to that common set. Either set as described above can be used to get the limit, and there may be other means to get the limit as well.
* Using indicator functions: let formula_14 equal formula_15 if formula_16 and formula_17 otherwise. Define formula_18 and formula_19 where the expressions inside the brackets on the right are, respectively, the limit infimum and limit supremum of the real-valued sequence formula_20 Again, if these two sets are equal, then the set-theoretic limit of the sequence formula_13 exists and is equal to that common set, and either set as described above can be used to get the limit.

To see the equivalence of the definitions, consider the limit infimum. The use of De Morgan&#x27;s law below explains why this suffices for the limit supremum. Since indicator functions take only values formula_17 and formula_23 formula_24 if and only if formula_14 takes value formula_17 only finitely many times. Equivalently, 
formula_27 
if and only if there exists formula_28 such that the element is in formula_29 for every formula_30 which is to say if and only if formula_31 for only finitely many formula_32 
Therefore, formula_33 is in the formula_34 if and only if formula_33 is in all but finitely many formula_36 For this reason, a shorthand phrase for the limit infimum is &quot;formula_33 is in formula_13 all but finitely often&quot;, typically expressed by writing &quot;formula_13 a.b.f.o.&quot;.

Similarly, an element formula_33 is in the limit supremum if, no matter how large formula_28 is, there exists formula_42 such that the element is in formula_43 That is, formula_33 is in the limit supremum if and only if formula_33 is in infinitely many formula_36 For this reason, a shorthand phrase for the limit supremum is &quot;formula_33 is in formula_13 infinitely often&quot;, typically expressed by writing &quot;formula_13 i.o.&quot;.

To put it another way, the limit infimum consists of elements that &quot;eventually stay forever&quot; (are in set after formula_28), while the limit supremum consists of elements that &quot;never leave forever&quot; (are in set after formula_28). Or more formally:

